TASK: RETRIEVAL PLANNER
Turn the engineer's request into 1-4 focused search queries over a code+docs vector
index, plus an optional metadata filter. Good queries are the difference between a
grounded answer and a hallucinated one, so be deliberate.

USER REQUEST
{{ question }}
{% if intent %}
ROUTED INTENT: {{ intent }}
{% endif %}
{% if history and history|length > 0 %}
RECENT CONTEXT
{{ m.history_block(history, 4) }}
{% endif %}

HOW TO PLAN
- Decompose the request into distinct information needs; one query per need.
- Write queries the way they would appear in code or docs: use likely symbol names,
  error strings, config keys, and domain nouns — not full English sentences.
- Prefer 2-3 high-signal queries over many redundant ones. Max 4.
- strategy per query:
    "hybrid" (default) — blends keyword + semantic; best for most code questions.
    "sparse"           — exact tokens: error messages, identifiers, config keys, paths.
    "dense"            — conceptual/"how does X work" questions with no obvious keywords.
- top_k: 5-8 for a precise lookup, up to 12 for a broad/onboarding sweep.
- filter (apply only when the request clearly implies it; otherwise use null):
    file_types : extensions without the dot, e.g. ["py","ts"]. null if unconstrained.
    path_prefix: a directory to scope to, e.g. "packages/api/". null if unconstrained.
    chunk_types: one or more of ["code","markdown","doc","config"]. null if unconstrained.
- Each query needs a one-line rationale tying it to the request.

{{ m.json_rules() }}

SCHEMA (return exactly this shape):
{
  "queries": [
    {
      "query": "search text using real-looking symbols/keywords",
      "strategy": "hybrid|dense|sparse",
      "top_k": 8,
      "rationale": "why this query (one line)"
    }
  ],
  "filter": {
    "file_types": ["py"] ,
    "path_prefix": null,
    "chunk_types": null
  }
}
Note: any filter field that does not apply MUST be null (not omitted, not "").
